tronage for their authors and good publicity for the German principalities in which they lived and worked. Cameralism, then, was the public face of the prince's most secret affairs; as such, it was an essentially dishonest enterprise. In an entertaining series of case studies on mining, textiles, forestry, and universities, Wakefield portrays cameralists in their own gritty terms. The result is a revolutionary new understanding about how the sciences created and maintained an image of the well-ordered police state in early modern Germany. In raising doubts about the status of these German sciences of the state, Wakefield ultimately questions many of our accepted narratives about science, culture, and society in early modern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMercantile systemzGermanyxHistoryy17th century. 0aMercantile systemzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acameral sciences, cameralism, germany, policing, surveillance, law, legal system, police state, power, authority, discipline, patronage, mining, textiles, forestry, university, education, history, politics, political science, administration, public officials, mercantile, capitalism, silver, ironworks, factory, labor, faculty, knowledge, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022687020540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226870229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226870229/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles